        "heading": "SECTION 1: THE PROBLEM",
        "content": "### H2: Why DeFi Protocols Fail — and Why It Almost Always Comes Down to the First Four Weeks\n\nThe DeFi exploit headlines are the visible failure mode. The invisible one is more common and more expensive: the protocol that launches, attracts liquidity, and then dies slowly because the tokenomics were broken from day one.\n\nA DeFi protocol is not a product. It is an economic system. Every variable — fee rate, reward emission schedule, collateralization ratio, liquidation threshold, governance weight — interacts with every other variable. A slight miscalibration in the emission schedule can create a mercenary liquidity dynamic where capital enters, farms rewards, and exits within days, leaving the protocol insolvent. A liquidation threshold set too conservatively can lead to bad debt accumulation under market stress conditions. A fee rate set too high relative to competitors kills volume before the protocol establishes network effects.\n\nThese failures are not engineering failures. They are economic design failures — and they are almost always set in motion before a developer writes a line of code.\n\nThe second failure mode is the security exploit. What makes DeFi protocols uniquely vulnerable compared to ordinary smart contracts is the combination of composability and liquidity. A DeFi protocol with $10M in TVL is an on-chain target that can be attacked from anywhere in the world, at any time, using capital borrowed and returned within a single block. The attack surface is not just your contracts — it is every protocol your contracts interact with, every oracle you rely on, and every assumption your contracts make about external state.\n\nThe third failure mode is regulatory. The DeFi regulatory environment is changing faster than any other area of crypto. Protocols built without compliance architecture face retroactive regulatory risk in the jurisdictions where their users are located. Getting this wrong does not just mean a fine — it means the protocol gets shut down.\n\n---"
