    "faq": [
      {
        "question": "Q: What is the safest type of DeFi yield?",
        "answer": "Lending stablecoins to established protocols (Aave, Compound) for 3-7% APY represents the lower end of DeFi risk — the main risks are smart contract bugs and stablecoin depeg. Higher yields (20%+) carry correspondingly higher risks (token price risk, newer protocol smart contract risk, liquidation risk)."
      },
      {
        "question": "Q: What is the difference between APR and APY in DeFi?",
        "answer": "APR (Annual Percentage Rate) doesn't account for compounding. APY (Annual Percentage Yield) accounts for compounding frequency. Most DeFi protocols report APR; if you manually compound weekly, your actual return approaches APY. Auto-compounding vaults advertise APY since compounding is built in."
      },
      {
        "question": "Q: Is DeFi yield taxable in the US?",
        "answer": "Yes — the IRS treats DeFi yield as ordinary income at the time it's received. Each reward claim is a taxable event at the fair market value when received. Gains or losses on the token itself are capital gains/losses when sold. Track all yield receipt events for tax reporting."
      },
      {
        "question": "Q: What happens to my DeFi position if the internet goes down?",
        "answer": "Your on-chain position (tokens in a smart contract) remains unchanged — blockchain state persists regardless of any internet outage. You would temporarily be unable to interact with it (add/remove funds, claim rewards), but your funds are safe. Decentralized protocols don't have servers that can go down."
      },
      {
        "question": "Q: Can I lose more than I deposit in DeFi?",
        "answer": "Generally not — most DeFi protocols are designed so your maximum loss is your deposited amount. Exceptions: protocols using leverage, where your collateral can be liquidated but typically no more than deposited. Some complex structured products can theoretically result in losses beyond initial deposit if using leverage within them."
      }
    ],
